Definition 3.3. A spectral functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$ is a DK-equivalence if • For every pair of objects $x,y\in Ob(\mathcal{A})$, the morphism in $\mathcal{S}$, $\mathcal{F}(x,y):\mathcal{A}(x,y)\to\mathcal{B}(x,y)$ is a stable equivalence of symmetric spectra. • The induced functor $[\mathcal{F}]:[\mathcal{A}]\to[\mathcal{B}]$ is an equivalence of ordinary categories.
Definition 4.19. We define a colored operad $\mathbb{LM}$ [HA, 4.2.1.4] as follows: • The set of objects of $\mathbb{LM}$ has two objects $\mathbb{a}$ and $\mathbb{m}$. • Let $\{X_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ be a finite collection of objects in $\mathbb{LM}$, and let $Y$ be a another object. If $Y=\mathbb{a}$, then $Mul_{\mathbb{LM}}(\{X_{i}\},Y)$ is the collection of all orderings on $I$ provided that each $X_{i}=\mathbb{a}$ and is empty otherwise. If $Y=\mathbb{m}$, then $Mul_{\mathbb{LM}}(\{X_{i}\},Y)$ is the collection of all orderings $\{i_{1}<\ldots<i_{n}\}$ on the set $I$ such that $X_{i_{n}}=\mathbb{m}$ and $X_{i_{j}}=\mathbb{a}$ for $j<n$. • The composition law on $\mathbb{LM}$ is determined by composing linear orderings in the natural way.
Definition 4.7. Let $p:X\to S$ be an inner fibration of simplicial sets (i.e. the fiber over any simplex of $S$ is an $\infty$-category), and let $f:x\to y$ be an edge of $X$, then $f$ is p-coCartesian if the natural map $X_{f/}\rightarrow X_{x/}\times_{S_{p(x)/}}S_{p(f)/}$ is a trivial Kan fibration (or if $f$ satisfies the properties of [T, 2.4.1.8]).
Definition 3.1. ➺ A braided system in a monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ is an ordered finite family $V_{1},V_{2},\ldots,V_{r}$ of objects in $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with a braiding, i.e. morphisms $\sigma_{i,j}:V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\rightarrow V_{j}\otimes V_{i}$ for $1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j}\leqslant r$ satisfying the colored Yang-Baxter equation (= cYBE) $(\sigma_{j,k}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{i})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{j}\otimes% \sigma_{i,k})\circ(\sigma_{i,j}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{k})=(\operatorname{Id% }_{k}\otimes\sigma_{i,j})\circ(\sigma_{i,k}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{j})\circ(% \operatorname{Id}_{i}\otimes\sigma_{j,k})$ on all the tensor products $V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\otimes V_{k}$ with $1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j\leqslant k}\leqslant r.$ (Here $\operatorname{Id}_{t}$ stands for $\operatorname{Id}_{V_{t}},$ $\;1\leqslant t\leqslant r.$) Such a system is denoted by $((V_{i})_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r};(\sigma_{i,j})_{1\leqslant i\leqslant j% \leqslant r})$ or briefly $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma}).$ ➺ The rank of a braided system is the number $r$ of its components. ➺ A braided morphism $\overline{f}:(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\rightarrow(\overline{W},% \overline{\xi})$ between two braided systems in $\mathcal{C}$ of the same rank $r$ is a collection of morphisms $(f_{i}\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(V_{i},W_{i}))_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r}$ respecting the braiding, i.e. $(f_{j}\otimes f_{i})\circ\sigma_{i,j}=\xi_{i,j}\circ(f_{i}\otimes f_{j})\quad% \forall\;1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j}\leqslant r.$ ➺ The category of rank $r$ braided systems and braided morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ is denoted by $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C}).$
Definition 2.8. A Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d (= YD) module structure over a bialgebra $H$ in a symmetric category $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a left $H$-module structure $\lambda$ and a right $H$-comodule structure $\delta$ on an object $M,$ satisfying the Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d compatibility condition (cf. Fig. 7) $(\operatorname{Id}_{M}\otimes\mu)\circ(\delta\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})% \circ c_{H,M}\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\lambda)\circ(\Delta\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{M})=$ $(\lambda\otimes\mu)\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes c_{H,M}\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ(\Delta\otimes\delta).$ The category of YD modules over a bialgebra $H$ (with, as morphisms, those which are simultaneously $H$-module and $H$-comodule morphisms) is denoted by ${{}_{H}}\!\mathbf{YD}^{H}.$
Definition 3.21. ➺ A degree $-1$ differential for a collection $(X_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ of objects in $\mathcal{C}$ is a family of morphisms $(d_{n}:X_{n}\rightarrow X_{n-1})_{n>0},$ satisfying $\displaystyle d_{n-1}\circ d_{n}$ $\displaystyle=0$ $\displaystyle\forall\>n>1.$ ➺ A bidegree $-1$ bidifferential for a collection $(X_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ of objects in $\mathcal{C}$ consists of two families of morphisms $(d_{n},d^{\prime}_{n}:X_{n}\rightarrow X_{n-1})_{n>0},$ satisfying $\displaystyle d_{n-1}\circ d_{n}$ $\displaystyle=d^{\prime}_{n-1}\circ d^{\prime}_{n}=d^{\prime}_{n-1}\circ d_{n}% +d_{n-1}\circ d^{\prime}_{n}=0$ $\displaystyle\forall\>n>1.$ ➺ An ordered tensor product for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ is a tensor product of the form $V_{1}^{\otimes m_{1}}\otimes V_{2}^{\otimes m_{2}}\otimes\cdots\otimes V_{r}^{% \otimes m_{r}},\qquad m_{i}\geqslant 0.$ ➺ The degree of such a tensor product is the sum $\sum_{i=1}^{r}m_{i}.$ ➺ The direct sum of all ordered tensor products of degree $n$ is denoted by $T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}.$ ➺ A (bi)degree $-1$ (bi)differential for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ is a (bi)degree $-1$ (bi)differential for $(T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow})_{n\geqslant 0}.$
Definition 2.2. An object $V$ in a monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ is called braided if it is endowed with a “local” braiding, i.e. a morphism $\sigma=\sigma_{V}:V\otimes V\rightarrow V\otimes V,$ satisfying the (categorical) Yang-Baxter equation (= YBE) $(\sigma_{V}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{V})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{V}\otimes% \sigma_{V})\circ(\sigma_{V}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{V})=(\operatorname{Id}_{V% }\otimes\sigma_{V})\circ(\sigma_{V}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{V})\circ(% \operatorname{Id}_{V}\otimes\sigma_{V}).$
Definition 3.3. A (left-right) Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d system over $H$ (= $H$-YD system) in $\mathcal{C}$ is an ordered finite family $V_{1},V_{2},\ldots,V_{r}$ of objects endowed with the following structure: 1. $(V_{1},\mu_{1},\nu_{1},\delta_{1})$ is an $H$-comodule algebra; 2. $(V_{r},\mu_{r},\nu_{r},\lambda_{r})$ is an $H$-module algebra; 3. $(V_{i},\mu_{i},\nu_{i},\lambda_{i},\delta_{i})$ is a YD module algebra over $H$ for all $1<i<r.$
Definition 3.24. The (bi)differentials from the above theorem and corollary are called multi-braided.
Definition 2.3. ➺ A monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ is called braided if it is endowed with a braiding (or a commutativity constraint), i.e. a natural family of morphisms $c=(c_{V,W}:V\otimes W\rightarrow W\otimes V)_{V,W\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal% {C})},$ satisfying $\displaystyle c_{V,W\otimes U}$ $\displaystyle=(\operatorname{Id}_{W}\otimes c_{V,U})\circ(c_{V,W}\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{U}),$ $\displaystyle c_{V\otimes W,U}$ $\displaystyle=(c_{V,U}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{W})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{V}% \otimes c_{W,U})$ for any triple of objects $V,W,U.$ “Natural” means here $c_{V^{\prime},W^{\prime}}\circ(f\otimes g)=(g\otimes f)\circ c_{V,W}$ for all $V,W,V^{\prime},W^{\prime}\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C}),f\in\operatorname{% Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(V,V^{\prime}),g\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(W,W^{% \prime}).$ ➺ A braided category $\mathcal{C}$ is called symmetric if its braiding is symmetric: $\displaystyle c_{V,W}\circ c_{W,V}$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{Id}_{W\otimes V}$ $\displaystyle\forall\>V,W\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C}).$
Definition 2.1. A strict monoidal (or tensor) category is a category $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with ➺ a tensor product bifunctor $\otimes:\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the associativity condition; ➺ a unit object $\mathbf{I}$ which is a left and right identity for $\otimes.$
Definition 3.2. ➺ A (left-right) Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d module algebra over $H$ is the datum of a UAA structure $(\mu,\nu)$ and a YD structure $(\lambda,\delta)$ on an object $V$ in $\mathcal{C},$ such that $\mu$ and $\nu$ are morphisms of YD modules (see (26), (27) and (17), (23) for the $H$-(co)module structure of $V\otimes V$ and of $\mathbf{I}$): $\displaystyle\delta\circ\mu$ $\displaystyle=(\mu\otimes\mu_{H})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{V}\otimes c_{H,V}% \otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ(\delta\otimes\delta),$ $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\mu)$ $\displaystyle=\mu\circ(\lambda\otimes\lambda)\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}% \otimes c_{H,V}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{V})\circ(\Delta_{H}^{op}\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{V\otimes V}),$ $\displaystyle\delta\circ\nu$ $\displaystyle=\nu\otimes\nu_{H},$ $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\nu)$ $\displaystyle=\varepsilon_{H}\otimes\nu.$ ➺ The category of YD module algebras over $H$ in $\mathcal{C}$ (with as morphisms those which are simultaneously UAA and YD module morphisms) is denoted by ${{}_{H}}\!\mathbf{YDAlg}^{H}.$ ➺ Omitting the comodule structure $\delta$ from the definition, one gets the notion of $H$-module algebra. $H$-comodule algebras are defined similarly.
Definition 2.14. A morphism $R:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow H\otimes H$ is called a weak R-matrix for a UAA and coUAA object $(H,\mu,\nu,\Delta,\varepsilon)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ if (cf. Fig. 11) 1. $(\Delta\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ R=(\operatorname{Id}_{H\otimes H}% \otimes\mu)\circ c^{2}\circ(R\otimes R),$ 2. $(\varepsilon\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ R=\nu,$ 3. $\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(R\otimes\Delta)=\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(\Delta^{op}\otimes R).$
Definition 3.22. A braided character for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ is a rank $r$ braided system morphism from $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ to $(\mathbf{I},\ldots,\mathbf{I};\sigma_{i,j}=\operatorname{Id}_{\mathbf{I}}% \forall\>i<j).$
Definition 2.16. A strong R-matrix is a weak R-matrix satisfying two additional axioms (Fig. 12): 1’. $(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\Delta)\circ R=(\mu^{op}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_% {H\otimes H})\circ c^{2}\circ(R\otimes R),$ 2’. $(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\varepsilon)\circ R=\nu.$
Definition 2.6. A bialgebra $H$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called quasi-triangular if it is endowed with an R-matrix, i.e. a morphism $R:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow H\otimes H$ satisfying the following conditions: 1. $(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\Delta)\circ R=(\mu^{op}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_% {H\otimes H})\circ c^{2}\circ(R\otimes R),$ 2. $(\Delta\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ R=(\operatorname{Id}_{H\otimes H}% \otimes\mu)\circ c^{2}\circ(R\otimes R),$ 3. $\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(R\otimes\Delta)=\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(\Delta^{op}\otimes R),$ where $c^{2}$ is a shorthand notation for $\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes c_{H,H}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H},$ $\mu_{H\otimes H}:=(\mu\otimes\mu)\circ c^{2}:(H\otimes H)\otimes(H\otimes H)% \rightarrow H\otimes H$ is the standard multiplication on the tensor product of two UAAs, and $\mu^{op}:=\mu\circ c_{H,H},\qquad\qquad\qquad\Delta^{op}:=c_{H,H}\circ\Delta$ are the twisted multiplication and comultiplication respectively. The R-matrix $R$ is called invertible if there exists a morphism $R^{-1}:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow H\otimes H$ such that $\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(R\otimes R^{-1})=\mu_{H\otimes H}\circ(R^{-1}\otimes R)=% \nu\otimes\nu.$
Definition 2.5. ➺ A unital associative algebra (= UAA) in $\mathcal{C}$ is an object $A$ together with morphisms $\mu:A\otimes A\rightarrow A$ and $\nu:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow A$ satisfying the associativity and the unit conditions: $\displaystyle\mu\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{A}\otimes\mu)$ $\displaystyle=\mu\circ(\mu\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{A}):A^{\otimes 3}% \rightarrow A,$ $\displaystyle\mu\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{A}\otimes\nu)$ $\displaystyle=\mu\circ(\nu\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{A})=\operatorname{Id}_{A}.$ A UAA morphism $\varphi$ between UAAs $(A,\mu_{A},\nu_{A})$ and $(B,\mu_{B},\nu_{B})$ is a $\varphi\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(A,B)$ respecting the UAA structures: $\displaystyle\varphi\circ\mu_{A}$ $\displaystyle=\mu_{B}\circ(\varphi\otimes\varphi):A\otimes A\rightarrow B,$ $\displaystyle\varphi\circ\nu_{A}$ $\displaystyle=\nu_{B}.$ ➺ A UAA $(A,\mu,\nu)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called braided if it is endowed with a braiding $\sigma$ compatible with the UAA structure. Using notation (1), this can be written as $\displaystyle\sigma\circ\mu^{1}$ $\displaystyle=\mu^{2}\circ(\sigma^{1}\circ\sigma^{2}):A^{\otimes 3}\rightarrow A% ^{\otimes 2},$ $\displaystyle\sigma\circ\mu^{2}$ $\displaystyle=\mu^{1}\circ(\sigma^{2}\circ\sigma^{1}):A^{\otimes 3}\rightarrow A% ^{\otimes 2};$ $\displaystyle\sigma\circ\nu^{1}$ $\displaystyle=\nu^{2}:A=\mathbf{I}\otimes A=A\otimes\mathbf{I}\rightarrow A^{% \otimes 2},$ $\displaystyle\sigma\circ\nu^{2}$ $\displaystyle=\nu^{1}:A=\mathbf{I}\otimes A=A\otimes\mathbf{I}\rightarrow A^{% \otimes 2}.$ ➺ A counital coassociative coalgebra (= coUAA) in $\mathcal{C}$ is an object $C$ together with morphisms $\Delta:C\rightarrow C\otimes C$ and $\varepsilon:C\rightarrow\mathbf{I}$ satisfying the coassociativity and the counit conditions: $\displaystyle(\Delta\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{C})\circ\Delta$ $\displaystyle=(\operatorname{Id}_{C}\otimes\Delta)\circ\Delta:C\rightarrow C^{% \otimes 3},$ $\displaystyle(\varepsilon\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{C})\circ\Delta$ $\displaystyle=(\operatorname{Id}_{C}\otimes\varepsilon)\circ\Delta=% \operatorname{Id}_{C}.$ A coUAA morphism $\varphi$ between coUAAs is a morphism in $\mathcal{C}$ respecting the coUAA structures. ➺ A coUAA $(C,\Delta,\varepsilon)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called braided if it is endowed with a braiding $\sigma$ compatible with the coUAA structure, in the sense analogous to (8)-(11). ➺ A left module over a UAA $(A,\mu,\nu)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is an object $M$ together with a morphism $\lambda:A\otimes M\rightarrow M$ respecting $\mu$ and $\nu$: $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\mu\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{M})$ $\displaystyle=\lambda\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{A}\otimes\lambda):A\otimes A% \otimes M\rightarrow M,$ $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\nu\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{M})$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{Id}_{M}.$ An $A$-module morphism $\varphi$ between $A$-modules $(M,\lambda_{M})$ and $(N,\lambda_{N})$ is a $\varphi\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(M,N)$ respecting the $A$-module structures: $\displaystyle\varphi\circ\lambda_{M}$ $\displaystyle=\lambda_{N}\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{A}\otimes\varphi):A\otimes M% \rightarrow N.$ The category of $A$-modules in $\mathcal{C}$ and their morphisms is denoted by ${}_{A}\!\mathbf{Mod}.$ Right modules, left/right comodules over coUAAs and their morphisms are defined similarly. ➺ A bialgebra in a braided category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,\mathbf{I},c)$ is a UAA structure $(\mu,\nu)$ and a coUAA structure $(\Delta,\varepsilon)$ on an object $H,$ compatible in the following sense: $\displaystyle\Delta\circ\mu$ $\displaystyle=(\mu\otimes\mu)\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes c_{H,H}\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ(\Delta\otimes\Delta):H\otimes H\rightarrow H% \otimes H,$ $\displaystyle\Delta\circ\nu$ $\displaystyle=\nu\otimes\nu:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow H\otimes H,$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon\circ\mu$ $\displaystyle=\varepsilon\otimes\varepsilon:H\otimes H\rightarrow\mathbf{I},$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon\circ\nu$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{Id}_{\mathbf{I}}:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow\mathbf{I}.$ A bialgebra morphism is a morphism which respects UAA and coUAA structures simultaneously. ➺ If moreover $H$ has an antipode, i.e. a morphism $s:H\rightarrow H$ satisfying $\mu\circ(s\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ\Delta=\mu\circ(\operatorname{Id}_% {H}\otimes s)\circ\Delta=\nu\circ\varepsilon,$ then it is called a Hopf algebra in $\mathcal{C}.$
Definition 3.2. A dg category $\mathcal{C}$ is pretriangulated if it has a zero object, $\ast$, such that the following properties hold. (1) (Closure under shifts) For an $X$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and an $n$ in $\mathbb{Z}$ the dg $\mathcal{C}$-module $\Sigma^{n}\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,-)$ given by $\left(\Sigma^{n}\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Z)\right)_{n+k}=% \operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Z)_{k}$ with differential $d(\Sigma^{n}f)=(-1)^{n}\cdot\Sigma^{n}(df)$ is representable. (2) (Closure under cones) Given a 0-cycle in $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ the dg $\mathcal{C}$-module $M$ given by $M(Z)_{k}=\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(Y,Z)_{k}\oplus\operatorname% {\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Z)_{k+1}$ with differential $d(a,b)=(d(a),af-d(b))$ is representable.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be an additive category and $F\colon\mathcal{T}\rightarrow\mathcal{T}$ a self-equivalence of $\mathcal{T}$. The orbit category of $\mathcal{T}$ by $F$ is the category $\mathcal{T}/F$ with objects those of $\mathcal{T}$ and morphisms defined by $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{T}/F}(X,Y)=\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}% \operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{T}}(X,F^{n}Y).$
Définition 1.2. Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm nul}$, $E$ un ensemble fini, $I$ une partie de $E$ et $\mathbf{a}=(a_{i})_{i\in E}$ une famille d’objets de ${\mathcal{M}}$. On note $\epsilon_{I}(\mathbf{a})$ l’endomorphisme $\underset{i\in E}{\bigoplus}f_{i}$ de l’objet $\underset{i\in E}{\bigoplus}a_{i}$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, où $f_{i}$ est l’endomorphisme identique de $a_{i}$ lorsque $i\in I$ et l’endomorphisme nul de $a_{i}$ lorsque $i\notin I$.
Définition 1.8 (Foncteurs polynomiaux). Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm nul}$, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie additive dont les idempotents se scindent, $d\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{-\infty\}$ et $F:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On dit que $F$ est polynomial de degré au plus $d$ si le foncteur $cr_{d+1}(F):{\mathcal{M}}^{d+1}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ est nul. Le degré de $F$ est par définition le plus petit $d$ vérifiant cette propriété. On note ${\mathcal{P}}ol_{d}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{A}})$ la sous-catégorie pleine de $\mathbf{Fct}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{A}})$ dont les objets sont les foncteurs polynomiaux de degré au plus $d$.
Définition 1.9. Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm nul}$, $x$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}$ et ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie additive dont les idempotents se scindent. On définit un foncteur $\delta_{x}:\mathbf{Fct}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{A}})\to\mathbf{Fct}({\mathcal{% M}},{\mathcal{A}})$ naturel en $x$ par $\delta_{x}(F)={\rm Im}\,(1-\varepsilon)$, où $\varepsilon$ est l’endomorphisme idempotent de $\tau_{x}(F)$ induit par l’endomorphisme idempotent $0$ de $x$ (on utilise la fonctorialité de $x\mapsto\tau_{x}$). On dispose ainsi d’un isomorphisme naturel $\tau_{x}(F)\simeq F\oplus\delta_{x}(F)$. Le foncteur $\delta_{x}$ s’appelle foncteur différence associé à $x$.
Définition 1.5 (Effets croisés). Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm nul}$, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie additive dont les idempotents se scindent, $E$ un ensemble fini, $\mathbf{a}=(a_{i})_{i\in E}$ une famille d’objets de ${\mathcal{M}}$ et $F:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On pose : $cr_{E}(F)(\mathbf{a}):={\rm Im}\,F(e_{E}(\mathbf{a})),$ où $e_{E}(\mathbf{a})$ est l’idempotent introduit dans le corollaire précédent. Le foncteur $cr_{d}(F):{\mathcal{M}}^{d}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ sera appelé $d$-ème effet croisé de $F$.
Définition 1.13. Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm ini}$, $x$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}$, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie abélienne, et $F:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On note $\kappa_{x}(F)$ (resp. $\delta_{x}(F)$) le noyau (resp. conoyau) du morphisme $i_{x}(F):F=\tau_{0}(F)\to\tau_{x}(F)$ de $\mathbf{Fct}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{A}})$ induit par l’unique morphisme $0\to x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$. L’endofoncteur $\delta_{x}$ de $\mathbf{Fct}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{A}})$ s’appelle foncteur différence associé à $x$.
Définition 3.1. On dit qu’une catégorie ${\mathcal{C}}$ vérifie : 1. la propriété $(FE)$ si pour tout objet $x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, le monoïde ${\rm End}_{\mathcal{C}}(x)$ est de type fini ; 2. la propriété $(EI)$ si tout endomorphisme de ${\mathcal{C}}$ est un isomorphisme.
Définition 2.4. Soient ${\mathcal{C}}$ une petite catégorie, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie abélienne et $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. 1. On dit que $F$ est ponctuellement de type fini (resp. ponctuellement noethérien) si $F(c)$ est un objet de type fini (resp. noethérien) dans la catégorie ${\mathcal{A}}$ pour tout objet $c$ de ${\mathcal{C}}$. 2. On dit que $F$ est faiblement ponctuellement de type fini (resp. faiblement ponctuellement noethérien) si $F(c)$ est un objet de type fini (resp. noethérien) dans la catégorie des objets de ${\mathcal{A}}$ munis d’une action du monoïde ${\rm End}_{\mathcal{C}}(c)$ pour tout objet $c$ de ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Définition 2.11. Soient ${\mathcal{C}}$ une petite catégorie, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie abélienne et $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On dira que $F$ est presque nul si l’ensemble des classes d’isomorphisme d’objets $c$ de ${\mathcal{C}}$ tels que $F(c)\neq 0$ est fini.
Définition 2.5. On dit qu’une catégorie ${\mathcal{C}}$ vérifie la propriété $(FM)$ si pour tous objets $t$ et $x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, le ${\rm End}_{\mathcal{C}}(x)$-ensemble ${\mathcal{C}}(t,x)$ est de type fini.
Définition 3.2. Soit $({\mathcal{M}},+,0)$ une catégorie monoïdale symétrique. 1. On dira qu’un ensemble $T$ d’objets de ${\mathcal{M}}$ est générateur monoïdal (resp. générateur monoïdal faible) de $({\mathcal{M}},+,0)$ (ou simplement, par abus, de ${\mathcal{M}}$) si tout objet de ${\mathcal{M}}$ est isomorphe à une somme finie (resp. à un facteur direct d’une somme finie), au sens de $+$, d’éléments de $T$. 2. On notera $(P_{0})$ la propriété suivante de $({\mathcal{M}},+,0)$ : il existe un ensemble générateur monoïdal faible fini. 3. On dira que $({\mathcal{M}},+,0)$ est une pseudo-théorie si elle possède un ensemble générateur monoïdal réduit à un élément, i.e. s’il existe $a\in{\rm Ob}\,{\mathcal{M}}$ tel que tout objet de ${\mathcal{M}}$ soit isomorphe à $a^{+n}$ pour un $n\in\mathbb{N}$. Si l’on peut faire en sorte que cet entier soit toujours unique, nous dirons que ${\mathcal{M}}$ est une pseudo-théorie régulière. 4. Nous dirons que ${\mathcal{M}}$ vérifie la propriété $(P_{1})$ si pour tout objet $x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, l’ensemble des classes d’isomorphisme d’objets de ${\mathcal{M}}$ n’appartenant pas à l’image essentielle de l’endofoncteur $x+-$ est fini. 5. Nous dirons que ${\mathcal{M}}$ vérifie la propriété $(P_{2})$ si pour tout ensemble fini $E$ d’objets de ${\mathcal{M}}$, il existe un objet $x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$ tel qu’aucun des éléments de $E$ n’appartienne à l’image essentielle de l’endofoncteur $x+-$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$. 6. Nous dirons que ${\mathcal{M}}$ vérifie la propriété $(P_{3})$ si pour tous objets $x$ et $t$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, l’ensemble des classes d’isomorphisme d’objets $y$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$ tel qu’existe un morphisme $x\to y$ ne se factorisant pas par le morphisme canonique $x\to x+t$ est fini. 7. On dira que ${\mathcal{M}}$ vérifie la propriété $(P_{4})$ si pour tous objets $t$ et $a$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, il existe un ensemble fini d’objets $U(a,t)$ tel que, pour tout objet $x$ et tout morphisme $f:a\to t+x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, il existe un élément $b$ de $U(a,t)$ et des morphismes $u\in{\mathcal{M}}(a,t+b)$ et $g\in{\mathcal{M}}(b,x)$ tels que $f$ coïncide avec la composée $a\xrightarrow{u}t+b\xrightarrow{t+g}t+x.$
Définition 2.8. Soient ${\mathcal{M}}$ un objet de ${\mathcal{M}}on_{\rm ini}$, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie abélienne et $F:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On dira que $F$ est fortement noethérien si, pour tout objet $x$ de ${\mathcal{M}}$, le foncteur $\tau_{x}(F)$ est noethérien.
Définition 2.13. Soient ${\mathcal{C}}$ une petite catégorie, ${\mathcal{A}}$ une catégorie abélienne et $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ un foncteur. On dit q Notation 2.14. Dans tout cet article, si $A$ est un objet d’une catégorie additive ${\mathcal{A}}$ et $E$ un ensemble fini, on note $A[E]$ la somme directe de copies de $A$ indexées par $E$. On étend cette notation au cas où $E$ est infini si ${\mathcal{A}}$ possède des sommes infinies. ue $F$ est presque noethérien s’il existe un sous-foncteur $G$ presque nul de $F$ tel que $F/G$ soit noethérien.
Definition 1 (Second-order algebraic theories) A second-order algebraic theory consists of a cartesian category $\mathbb{T}$ and a strict cartesian identity-on-objects functor $\mathbf{M}\mathrel{\xy\ar(0)^{-}{}_{-}{}\endxy}\mathbb{T}$ that preserves the exponentiable object $({0})$.
Definition 1.10 A basic homomorphism $f:M(E,I)\to M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime})$ is called independence preserving if for all $a,b\in E$, the following implication is carried out $(a,b)\in I\Rightarrow(f(a)\not=f(b))~{}\vee~{}(f(a)=f(b)=1)~{}.$
Definition 3.3 A morphism $(\eta,\sigma):(M(E,I),X)\to(M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime}),X^{\prime})$ of state spaces is independence preserving if $\eta:M(E,I)\to M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime})$ is independence preserving.
Definition 3.8 A morphism of weak asynchronous systems $(f,\sigma):{\mathcal{A}}\to{\mathcal{A}}^{\prime}$ consists of partial maps $f:E{\rightharpoonup}E^{\prime}$ and $\sigma:S{\rightharpoonup}S^{\prime}$ satifying the following conditions (i) $\sigma(s_{0})=s^{\prime}_{0}$; (ii) for any triple $(s_{1},e,s_{2})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$, there is an alternative $\left\{\begin{array}[]{cl}(\sigma(s_{1}),f(e),\sigma(s_{2}))\in\operatorname{{% \rm Tran}}^{\prime},&\mbox{ if }f(e)\mbox{ is defined},\\ \sigma(s_{1})=\sigma(s_{2}),&\mbox{ if }f(e)\mbox{ is undefined},\end{array}\right.$ (iii) for each pair $(e_{1},e_{2})\in I$ such that $f(e_{1})$ and $f(e_{2})$ are defined, the pair $(f(e_{1}),f(e_{2}))$ must belong to $I^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.1 A morphism of state spaces $(M(E,I),X)\to(M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime}),X^{\prime})$ is a pair $(\eta,\sigma)$ where $\eta:M(E,I)\to M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime})$ is a basic homomorphism and $\sigma:X\to X^{\prime}\circ\eta^{op}$ is a natural transformation.
Definition 3.9 A morphism of weak asynchronous systems $(f,\sigma):{\mathcal{A}}\to{\mathcal{A}}^{\prime}$ is polygonal if $(f,\sigma)$ defines the independence preserving morphism of the corresponding state spaces.
Definition 1.11 Let $E$ be a set. A partial independence relation on $E$ is a subset $R\subseteq E_{*}\times E_{*}$ satisfying the followng conditions: (i) $(\forall a\in E_{*})~{}(a,*)\in R~{}\&~{}(*,a)\in R$; (ii) $(\forall a\in E_{*})~{}(a,a)\in R\Rightarrow a=*$; (iii) $(\forall a,b\in E_{*})~{}(a,b)\in R\Leftrightarrow(b,a)\in R$.
Definition 3.6 The weak asynchronous system ${\mathcal{A}}=(S,s_{0},E,I,\operatorname{{\rm Tran}})$ consist of a set $S$ which elements called states, an initial state $s_{0}\in S_{*}$, a set $E$ of events, the irreflective symmetric relation $I\subseteq E\times E$ of independence, satisfying the conditions • If $(s,a,s^{\prime})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$ $\&$ $(s,a,s^{\prime\prime})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$, then $s^{\prime}=s^{\prime\prime}$. • If $(a,b)\in I~{}\&~{}(s,a,s^{\prime})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}~{}\&~{}(s^{% \prime},b,s^{\prime\prime})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$, then there exists $s_{1}\in S$ such that $(s,b,s_{1})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$ $\&$ $(s_{1},a,s^{\prime\prime})\in\operatorname{{\rm Tran}}$.
Definition 1.1 Let $E$ be a set and let $I$ be an independence relation. A trace monoid $M(E,I)$ is the set of equivalence classes $[w]$ of all $w\in E^{*}$ with the operation $[w_{1}][w_{2}]=[w_{1}w_{2}]$ for $w_{1},w_{2}\in E^{*}$.
Definition 1.2 A homomorphism $f:M(E,I)\to M(E^{\prime},I^{\prime})$ is basic if $f(E)\subseteq E^{\prime}\cup\{1\}$.
Definition 6.4. For a strict traced symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$, define a set $M$ of atomic morphisms, such that any morphism in $\mathcal{C}$ can be obtained from those morphisms and the traced symmetric structure. An labelled morphism is called disconnected if it is of the form $f=f_{1}\otimes\ldots\otimes f_{K}$, where each $f_{k}$ is a labelled morphism in $M$: $f_{k}:X_{i_{k,1}}\otimes\ldots X_{i_{k,M_{k}}}\rightarrow Y_{j_{k,1}}\otimes% \ldots\otimes Y_{j_{k,N_{k}}}$
Definition 4.5. For a monoidal signature $\textbf{Sig}(\mathcal{A})$, a traced symmetric monoidal category $\mathbb{F}(T)$ is called the free traced SMC when, for any traced SMC $\mathcal{C}$, there exists a valuation $\eta\in\textrm{ob}([\textbf{Sig}(\mathcal{A}),\mathcal{C}])$ such that: $(-\circ\eta):\textrm{\bf TSMC}(\mathbb{F}(T),\mathcal{C})\to[T,\mathcal{C}]$ yields an equivalence of categories.
Definition 2.4. An Einstein expression over an alphabet $\mathcal{A}$ is a list of $\delta$-elements and (possibly relabelled) tensor symbols, where each label is either distinct or occurs as a repeated upper and lower label.
Definition 4.3. A (small, strict) monoidal signature $T=(O,M,\textrm{\rm dom},\textrm{\rm cod})$ consists of a set of objects $O$, a set of morphisms $M$, and a pair of functions $\textrm{\rm dom}:M\rightarrow O^{*}$ and $\textrm{\rm cod}:M\rightarrow O^{*}$.
Definition 6.6. Let $f$ and $f^{\prime}$ be given as in Definition 6.5. A component $f_{k}$ of $f$ is said to be totally contracted if the indices of all of its inputs occur in $\{i_{1},\ldots,i_{P}\}$ and the indices of all of its outputs occur in $\{j_{1},\ldots,j_{P}\}$.
Definition 6.1. For a set $\mathcal{L}$ of labels and a function $\mu:\mathcal{L}\to\textrm{ob}(\mathcal{C})$, an object is called $\mu$-labelled if it is equipped with a list $\vec{i}$ such that: $X=\mu(i_{1})\otimes\mu(i_{2})\otimes\ldots\otimes\mu(i_{n})$ A morphism is called $\mu$-labelled if its domain and codomain have $\mu$-labellings for disjoint lists $\vec{i}$, $\vec{j}$.
Definition 2.1. A (small) abstract tensor system consists of: • A set $\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$ for all $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\in\mathcal{P}_{f}(\mathcal{L})$ such that $\mathbf{x}\cap\mathbf{y}=\emptyset$, • a tensor product operation: $(-\cdot-):\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\times\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x}^{% \prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\to\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x}\cup\mathbf{x}^{\prime},% \mathbf{y}\cup\mathbf{y}^{\prime})$ defined whenever $(\mathbf{x}\cup\mathbf{y})\cap(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\cup\mathbf{y}^{\prime})=\emptyset$ • a contraction function for $a\in\mathbf{x},b\in\mathbf{y}$ such that $\tau(a)=\tau(b)$: $\mathcal{K}_{a}^{b}:\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\to\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x% }-\{a\},\mathbf{y}-\{b\})$ • a bijection between sets of tensors, called a relabelling: $r_{f}:\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\overset{\sim}{\to}\mathcal{T}(f(% \mathbf{x}),f(\mathbf{y}))$ for every bijection $f:(\mathbf{x}\cup\mathbf{y})\overset{\sim}{\to}\mathbf{z}$ such that $\tau(f(x))=\tau(x)$ for all $x\in\mathbf{x}\cup\mathbf{y}$, • a chosen tensor called a $\delta$-element $\delta_{a}^{b}\in\mathcal{T}(\{a\},\{b\})$ for all $a,b$ such that $\tau(a)=\tau(b)$, along with an “empty” $\delta$-element $1\in\mathcal{T}(\emptyset,\emptyset)$
Definition 6.5. Let $f=f_{1}\otimes\ldots\otimes f_{M}$ be a disconnected labelled morphism. For distinct indices $\{i_{1},\ldots,i_{P}\}\subseteq\{i_{1,1},\ldots i_{K,M_{K}}\}$ and $\{j_{1},\ldots,j_{P}\}\subseteq\{j_{1,1},\ldots j_{K,N_{K}}\}$, a map $f^{\prime}$ is said to be in contraction normal form (CNF) if: $f^{\prime}=C_{i_{1}}^{j_{1}}(C_{i_{2}}^{j_{2}}(\ldots(C_{i_{P}}^{j_{P}}(f))% \ldots))$
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathcal{S}=(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{L},\mathcal{T}(-,-))$ an abstract tensor system with a choice of canonical labels $\mathcal{L}_{c}\subseteq\mathcal{L}$. Then $\mathbb{C}[\mathcal{S}]$ is the traced symmetric monoidal category defined as follows: $\displaystyle\textrm{ob}(\mathbb{C}[\mathcal{S}])$ $\displaystyle=\mathcal{U}^{*}$ $\displaystyle\hom_{\mathbb{C}[\mathcal{S}]}(\vec{X},\vec{Y})$ $\displaystyle=\mathcal{T}(\mathbf{x}^{\,(0)},\mathbf{y}^{\,(1)})$ $\displaystyle\vec{X}\otimes\vec{Y}$ $\displaystyle=\vec{X}\vec{Y}\quad(I=[\,])$ For $\psi:\vec{X}\to\vec{Y}$, $\phi:\vec{Y}\to\vec{Z}$, $\widetilde{\psi}:\vec{U}\to\vec{V}$, and $\xi:\vec{U}\otimes\vec{X}\to\vec{V}\otimes\vec{X}$, the rest of the structure is defined as: $\displaystyle\phi_{\vec{y}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{z}^{\,(1)}}\circ\psi_{\vec{x}^{\,(0)% }}^{\vec{y}^{\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle=\psi_{\vec{x}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{y^{\prime}}}\phi_{\vec{y^{\prime}}}% ^{\vec{z}^{\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle\psi_{\vec{x}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{y}^{\,(1)}}\otimes\widetilde{\psi}_{% \,\vec{u}^{\,(0)}}^{\,\vec{v}^{\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle=\psi_{\vec{x}_{1..m}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{y}_{1..n}^{\,(1)}}\widetilde% {\psi}_{\,\vec{u}_{m+1..m+m^{\prime}}^{\,(0)}}^{\,\vec{v}_{n+1..n+n^{\prime}}^% {\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle\textrm{id}_{\vec{X}}$ $\displaystyle=\delta_{\vec{x}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{x}^{\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle\sigma_{\vec{X},\vec{Y}}$ $\displaystyle=\delta_{\vec{x}_{1..m}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{x}_{n+1..n+m}^{\,(1)}}% \delta_{\vec{y}_{m+1..m+n}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{y}_{1..n}^{\,(1)}}$ $\displaystyle\textrm{Tr}^{\vec{X}}(\xi_{\vec{u}_{1..m}^{\,(0)}\vec{x}_{m+1..m+% k}^{\,(0)}}^{\vec{v}_{1..n}^{\,(1)}\vec{x}_{n+1..n+k}^{\,(1)}})$ $\displaystyle=\xi_{\vec{u}_{1..m}^{\,(0)}\vec{x^{\prime}}}^{\vec{v}_{1..n}^{(1% )}\vec{x^{\prime}}}$ where $\vec{x^{\prime}}$ and $\vec{y^{\prime}}$ are chosen as fresh (possibly non-canonical) labels.
